{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646064"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:25:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:25:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18155"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18155"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.07,0.69,0.1,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10869"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80662"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10869"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18155"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65958"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1212"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5325"},{"type":"tags","id":"7331"},{"type":"tags","id":"7366"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25283"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25287"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80662"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with difficulty in flexing her right thumb. She reports that she is unable to bend the tip of her thumb while trying to grip objects. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals weakness in flexion of the distal phalanx of the right thumb, but other movements of the thumb and fingers are intact.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following muscles is most likely affected in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Extensor pollicis longus","Abductor pollicis longus","Flexor pollicis longus","Flexor pollicis brevis","Opponens pollicis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s inability to flex the distal phalanx of the thumb suggests an issue with the \u003Cstrong\u003Eflexor pollicis longus (FPL)\u003C/strong\u003E. The FPL is the only muscle responsible for flexing the interphalangeal joint of the thumb. It is innervated by the anterior interosseous nerve, a branch of the median nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexor pollicis brevis\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in flexing the proximal phalanx of the thumb, not the distal phalanx.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbductor pollicis longus\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for abducting the thumb and does not contribute to flexion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpponens pollicis\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in opposition of the thumb, allowing it to touch the other fingers, but not in flexing the distal phalanx.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtensor pollicis longus\u003C/strong\u003E extends the thumb at the interphalangeal joint, which is the opposite action to flexion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The flexor pollicis longus (FPL) is responsible for flexing the thumb at the interphalangeal joint.","The FPL is innervated by the anterior interosseous nerve, a branch of the median nerve.","The FPL is the only muscle that flexes the distal phalanx of the thumb."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65958"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18155"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65958"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-22T08:14:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-22T08:15:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10869"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80662"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic S